---
import Prose from '../../layouts/Prose.astro';
import CastingWidget from '../../components/course/CastingWidget.astro';
import { TOOLS } from '../../lib/tools';

const tool = TOOLS.find((t) => t.slug === 'casting-practice')!;
---

<Prose
  title={tool.title}
  description={tool.description}
  crumbs={[{ name: 'Tools', href: '/tools/' }, { name: tool.title }]}
  kicker="Practice Tools"
>
  <p>
    The shield chart is pure arithmetic once the four Mothers are down: the Daughters are the
    Mothers read sideways, the Nieces are sums of adjacent pairs, the Witnesses sum the Nieces and
    the Judge sums the Witnesses: fifteen figures from four, every one determined. This tool
    casts four random Mothers and derives the whole shield, either at once or step by step with
    each addition explained as it lands.
  </p>
  <p>
    Use it the way <a href="/course/casting-the-chart/">Lesson 4</a> teaches: hand first. Cast
    and derive on paper, then let the step mode show you the same derivation and find where an
    error entered, if one did. A Judge with an odd number of points always means a miscast chart.
    The tool will never produce one, and neither should you. The full manual walkthrough, with
    the traditional procedure for making the Mothers from sixteen rows of points, is at
    <a href="/casting/">How to cast a chart</a>.
  </p>

  <CastingWidget />

  <p>
    When you can derive a shield by hand without hesitation, the worked charts of the course
    (<a href="/course/charts/">the course charts</a>) make good verification practice: derive
    them yourself and check against the canonical copies.
  </p>
</Prose>
